[2] Expert's commentary
Date: Tue 12 Feb 2013
From: Stefan Sobak <stefans@moag.gov.il> [edited]


Re: Horsemeat - Europe: control, food safety
-------------------------------------------
Compounds are approved for use in food producing animals when their use can be justified as safe for the health of consumers when these drugs are administered to the animals according to good veterinary practice. The regulator controls the use of the various drug molecules in food producing animals to ensure that their Minimal Residue Level (MRL) has not been exceeded indicating that the product can be regarded as safe. Non-compliance with the MRL is a violation and causes sanctions. If no MRL has been set, any detectable concentration of a molecule in the products is a violation because safety has not been established. Therefore, drug approval for the treatment of sporting or companion horses, not intended for slaughter for human consumption, is completely different than for horses regarded as "food producing animals."

There are specific compounds that are totally banned from veterinary use in food producing animals, regardless of the species, such as chloramphenicol, nitrofurans, nitroimidazoles, phenylbutazone etc., because they are not considered safe at any level. If any of those compounds is used in a horse, it can no longer be considered a food producing animal from the regulatory point of view. When horse meat is used illegally, illegal residues are a legitimate concern.

For detection of some banned drugs (e.g., chloramphenicol, malachite green, nitrofurans), laboratories are required to apply a "Minimum Required Performance Level (MRPL)" but it has nothing to do with a regulatory safety evaluation. However, for many banned compounds and the majority of compounds with no MRL, no MRPL's have been established. Any concentration detected below MRPL is a violation just the same. Laboratories generally monitor phenylbutazone at 5 ppb utilizing LOQ [limit of quantitation] of 2.5 ppb utilizing LC/MS/MS techniques, but it is not based on safety evaluation and any detected concentration is a violation.

--
Stefan Soback
Head, National Residue Control Laboratory
Kimron Veterinary Institute/Veterinary Services
Beit Dagan, Israel
<stefans@moag.gov.il>

[We are grateful to Prof Sobak for his clarifying commentary.

Laboratory test results for phenylbutazone in horse tissue samples from the involved European countries, such as Ireland, UK, France and others, are anticipated to become available, probably in the web-sites of the relevant national food-safety agencies. - Mod.AS]
